    <problem>
        <question id="2">
            <text>If the roots of the equation $x^2 - (a + 1)x + a + 4 = 0$ are negative,
                all possible values of the real number $a$ are in the interval $p \lt a \le q$.
                What is the ordered pair $(p, q)$? </text>
        </question>
        <solution>
            <text>(-4, -3).</text>
            <text>
                First, since the sum of the roots is $a + 1$ and both roots are negative, $a + 1 \lt
                0$; or $a \lt -1$. Next, the product of the roots is $a + 4$, so $a + 4 \gt 0$; or
                $a \gt -4$. Finally, the roots are real, so the discriminant must be non-negative.
                Hence, $a^2 - 2a - 15 \ge 0$, from which $a \le -3$ or $a \ge 5$. Taking the
                intersection of all three requirements, the roots will be negative precisely when
                $-4 \lt a \le -3$. Therefore we have $(p, q) = (-4, -3)$.
            </text>
        </solution>

    </problem>


    <problem>
        <question id="3">
            <image align="right">
                <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="200" height="170" class="image">
                    <polygon points="0,150 150,150 75,0" fill="white" stroke="black"></polygon>
                    <!-- left four-triangle -->
                    <polygon points="0,150 50,50 100,150" fill="lightgrey" stroke="black"></polygon>
